just_use dealer.go

# label: ELEGANT
# role: encodes domain knowledge

Dealer is autonomous: given a shuffled 104-card double deck,
it builds the board, deals two 15-card hands, and returns a
GameSetup "photo" any client (TS, Python, curl) can consume.
Gopher can set up a game without a Cat client in the loop.

Initial board is hard-coded (`initialBoardDefs`) — six stacks
pulled from deck 1 before dealing. Designer-chosen starting
position, not random. Parsed via the "KS", "TD" short labels
so the designer intent stays readable.

Mirrors `elm-port-docs/src/LynRummy/Dealer.elm` (a newer,
denser sidecar lives there — consult it for the full
algorithm including step-by-step deal logic and card
conservation invariants).

## Cross-language shuffle divergence

Go uses `math/rand.Shuffle` with a per-session seed generated
in `views/lynrummy_elm.go` at new-session time. Elm uses
Mulberry32 (`LynRummy.Random`) — different PRNG, different
output for the same seed. Same Fisher-Yates shape, different
bytes.

Practical implication: for the SAME seed, Elm's offline-mode
`dealFullGame` and Go's `DealFullGame` produce DIFFERENT
initial hands. This is benign because the two modes are
separate:

- Online mode: Elm hydrates from `/state` which carries the
  Go-dealt cards. The Elm Mulberry32 shuffle is never exercised.
- Offline mode: Elm uses its own Mulberry32 deal locally; no
  Go involvement.

If a cross-language test ever needs bit-for-bit deal parity,
port Mulberry32 to Go (or math/rand's Fisher-Yates to Elm) —
they can't be made to agree at runtime today.
